4.1 Unary Operation
Unary + / -
The operand should be either int or char.
+1 → 1
-1 → -1
+'a' → 97
-'a' → -97
-false → Error
Logical NOT
The operand must be of boolean; otherwise，return an error.
not true → false
not false → true
not 42 → Error
Bitwise NOT
Operand must be integral (int or char); result is int.
~0 → -1
~5 → -6
~true → Error
Type Cast
Java-style cast is supported for integral types:
Form Operand Result
(int) expr int, char int
(char) expr int, char char (signed 8-bit truncation)
(int) charValue converts char to int using sign extension.
(char) intValue converts using signed 8-bit truncation semantics.
(char) 56 → '8'
(int) 'c' → 99
(char) 300 → ','
Increment / Decrement
++30 → Error
30-- → Error


4.2 Multiplication/Division/Modulo
Left Oprand Right Oprand Result
int int int (integer arithmetic)
int char int (char promoted to int)
char int int (char promoted to int)
char char int (both promoted to int)
Note 1: Integer overflow wraps silently: 2147483647 * 2 = -2.
Note 2: Any other combination of operand types yields an error.
Note 3: Division by zero yields an error.


4.3 Addition/Subtraction
The operator + supports integral addition and string concatenation. If either operand is string, + performs
string concatenation. The operator - does not support string operands.
Left Oprand Right Oprand Result
int int int
int char int (char promoted to int before computation)
int string string (for + only)
char int int (char promoted to int before computation)
char char int (both promoted to int before computation)
char string string (for + only)
boolean string string (for + only)
string string string (for + only)
string int string (for + only)
string char string (for + only)
string boolean string (for + only)
Note: Any other combination of operand types yields an error.
"foo" + "bar" → "foobar"
"foo" + 42 → "foo42"
1 + "a" → "1a"
"foo" - "bar" → Error
'A' + 1 → 66
'A' + "!" → "A!"
"A" + true → "Atrue"


4.4 Shifting Operation
Both operands must be integral (int or char).
Operator Description Example
<< Signed left shift 1 << 4 = 16
>> Signed right shift -1 >> 1 = -1
>>> Unsigned right shift -1 >>> 1 = 2147483647
1 << 31 → -2147483648 (sign bit set)
'A' << 1 → 130
true << 2 → Error (shifts are integral-only)


4.5 Relational Operation Except for == and !=
Only integral types (int, char) support relational operators. Mismatched incompatible types produce
Error.
3 < 4 → true
'A' < 100 → true
true < 100 → Error


4.6 Equality (==, !=)
Left Right Behavior
int int compare the values
int char Promote char→int, compare
char int Promote char→int, compare
char char compare the values
boolean boolean compare the values
string string compare the strings
Note: Any other combination of operand types yields an error.
'A' == 65 → true
1 == true → Error


4.7 Bitwise Operation
Operands must be integral (int or char) and are evaluated as int.
Operator Example Result
& 255 & 15 15
^ 12 ^ 10 6
| 10 | 5 15
~ ~0 -1


4.8 Logical Operation
Both operands must be of boolean and short-circuit evaluation is required:
and: if left side is false, right side is not evaluated.
or: if left side is true, right side is not evaluated.
true and false → false
1 and true → Error


4.9 Ternary
cond ? thenExpr : elseExpr
cond must be of boolean; otherwise Error.
Right-associative: a ? b : c ? d : e → a ? b : (c ? d : e).
true ? 1 : 2 → 1